Section Summary: The chapter discusses the life and work of Joshua Reynolds, a prominent English artist of the 18th century. Reynolds' talent, industry, and common sense enabled him to achieve great work, and his time in Italy, where he studied and copied the works of masters, was invaluable to his development as an artist. He was influenced by various artists, including Michelangelo, Titian, and Rubens, and was able to take the best from each and apply it to his own work. After returning to England, Reynolds quickly gained success as a portrait painter, thanks to the quality of his work and the patronage he received, and he went on to become the first President of the Royal Academy. His legacy is marked by his ability to balance technique and inspiration, and his influence on the art world continues to be felt.
