Section section_02 (Chars 8674–11592):
Section Summary: Many artists are only interesting to talk to when discussing their own work, but some, like Sir Joshua Reynolds, are accomplished men of the world with broader interests. Reynolds was fortunate to have friendships with notable figures such as Dr. Johnson, Garrick, and Burke, which likely inspired and influenced him. Despite his intellectual curiosity, Reynolds had his flaws, including snobbery, jealousy, and vulgarity, which he partly overcame through his associations with refined people. However, these flaws sometimes led to lapses in taste, such as his ostentatious display of wealth. Overall, it is more interesting to see great men like Reynolds as they truly lived, with all their strengths and weaknesses, rather than trying to idealize them.
